<TEI xmlns="http://www.tei-c.org/ns/1.0" xmlns:frus="http://history.state.gov/frus/ns/1.0"><text><body><div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1915-11-10T14:00:00-05:00" frus:doc-dateTime-min="1915-11-10T14:00:00-05:00" n="854" subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d854">
                            <note rend="inline" type="source">File No. 341.115Am319/12</note>
                            <head>
                                <hi rend="italic">The Ambassador in Great Britain</hi> (<persName corresp="#p_PWH1" type="from"><hi rend="italic">Page</hi></persName>) <hi rend="italic">to the <gloss type="to">Secretary of State</gloss>
                                </hi>
                            </head>
                            <opener>
                                <seg rendition="#center">[Telegram]</seg>
                            </opener>
                            <opener>
                                <dateline rendition="#right">
                                    <placeName>
                                        <hi rend="smallcaps">London</hi></placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1915-11-10T19:00:00+00:00">
                                        <hi rend="italic">November 10, 1915, 7 p. m.</hi>
                                    </date>
                                    <lb/> [<hi rend="italic">Received 7.30 p. m.</hi>]</dateline>
                            </opener>
                            <p>3192. Your 2390, 3d [2d].<note n="2" xml:id="d854fn2">
                                    <hi rend="italic">Ante</hi>, <ref target="#pg_608">p.
                                    608</ref>.</note> Foreign Office informs me that British
                                Government have strongest belief that <hi rend="italic">Hocking</hi>
                                is entirely or to large extent enemy-owned, and therefore liable to
                                condemnation to that extent in accordance with the rules and
                                principles formerly observed by British prize court in such cases,
                                and adds that the case will be brought before a court and evidence
                                produced as soon as possible.</p>
                            <closer>
                                <signed>
                                    <hi rend="smallcaps">American Embassy</hi>
                                </signed>
                            </closer>
                        </div>
                        </body></text></TEI>